data.content:
In .NET 10, `Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi` upgraded from **OpenAPI.NET v1** to **v2**. This is a major breaking change in the underlying `Microsoft.OpenApi` library. Here's what changed and how to fix each piece:

---

## 1. `OpenApiString` / `OpenApiAny` removed

v2 uses native `JsonNode` instead of `IOpenApiAny` types.

```csharp
// Before
using Microsoft.OpenApi.Any;
param.Schema.Example = new OpenApiString("1.0");

// After
using System.Text.Json.Nodes;
param.Schema.Example = JsonValue.Create("1.0");
```

---

## 2. `OpenApiResponse` → responses are now keyed differently

`operation.Responses` changed from `OpenApiResponses` (a dictionary subclass) to `IDictionary<string, OpenApiResponse>`. The `TryAdd` call should still compile, but if you get errors, ensure you're not using removed helper methods.

```csharp
// This should still work in v2:
operation.Responses.TryAdd("401", new OpenApiResponse { Description = "Unauthorized" });
```

---

## 3. `OpenApiReference.Type` → `ReferenceType` enum replaced

`ReferenceType` moved/changed. Use the string-based `Type` property:

```csharp
// Before
Reference = new OpenApiReference { Type = ReferenceType.SecurityScheme, Id = "oauth2" }

// After
Reference = new OpenApiReference { Type = ReferenceType.SecurityScheme, Id = "oauth2" }
// If ReferenceType is gone, use:
Reference = new OpenApiReference { Id = "oauth2" }
```

In OpenAPI.NET v2, `OpenApiSecurityScheme` used in a requirement no longer needs a full `Reference` object. Instead use the document's `Components` to reference it, or simply set the `Id`:

```csharp
var oAuthScheme = new OpenApiSecurityScheme
{
    Reference = new OpenApiReference { Id = "oauth2" }
};
```

---

## 4. `schema.Nullable` removed

OpenAPI v3.1 (which v2 targets) removed `nullable` in favor of a `type` array that includes `"null"`. Use the `JsonSchemaType` flags:

```csharp
// Before
property.Value.Nullable = false;

// After — to explicitly mark as NOT nullable, remove "null" from Type:
property.Value.Type &= ~JsonSchemaType.Null;

// Or to SET nullable:
property.Value.Type |= JsonSchemaType.Null;
```

You'll need:
```csharp
using Microsoft.OpenApi.Models;  // JsonSchemaType is here
```

---

## Full migrated code

```csharp
using System.Text.Json.Nodes;
using Microsoft.OpenApi.Models;

options.AddOperationTransformer((operation, context, ct) =>
{
    var param = operation.Parameters.FirstOrDefault(p => p.Name == "api-version");
    if (param is not null)
    {
        param.Schema.Example = JsonValue.Create("1.0");
    }

    operation.Responses.TryAdd("401", new OpenApiResponse { Description = "Unauthorized" });

    var oAuthScheme = new OpenApiSecurityScheme
    {
        Reference = new OpenApiReference { Id = "oauth2" }
    };
    operation.Security = new List<OpenApiSecurityRequirement>
    {
        new() { [oAuthScheme] = scopes }
    };

    return Task.CompletedTask;
});

options.AddSchemaTransformer((schema, context, ct) =>
{
    if (schema.Properties is not null)
    {
        foreach (var property in schema.Properties)
        {
            if (schema.Required?.Contains(property.Key) != true)
                property.Value.Type &= ~JsonSchemaType.Null;
        }
    }
    return Task.CompletedTask;
});
```

**Summary of removals:** `Microsoft.OpenApi.Any` namespace is gone (use `System.Text.Json.Nodes`), `Nullable` property is gone (use `Type` flags), and `ReferenceType` may need adjustment depending on exact package version.
